    <Folder>
      <name>Season 1</name>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Feel Myanmar</name>
        <description>Tony met with culinary writer Ma Thanegi. They had pig’s-head salad with Kaffir lime leaf, long-bean salad with sesame and fish sauce, pennywort-leaf salad, a salad of Indian-style samosa.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            96.0906631,16.9583104,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Min Lan Seafood (Parami Branch)</name>
        <description>Tony had prawn curry here and cringed at the local cultural norm of making kissing noises to call a waiter over.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1573-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            96.139451,16.8540146,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name><![CDATA[Sofaer & Co]]></name>
        <description><![CDATA["Once one of the swankest department stores in Rangoon," says Tony. "Now people live here."]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1602-7CB342</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            96.1617348,16.7712781,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Seit Tine Kya</name>
        <description>Tea shop where Tony had morning tea with U Thiha Saw, a journalist. They had the hot black tea with a dollop of sweetened condensed milk and a fish soup.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1705-795548</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            96.1386425,16.8084563,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Taung Htate Pan Street</name>
        <description>Tony had a meal with Philippe Lajaunie, restaurateur, former owner of Brasserie Les Halles. They had chicken necks and cold beer. </description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            96.1766635,16.8796144,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Yangon</name>
        <description>Tony visited this town during Thadingyut, the Full Moon festival celebrated by Buddhists at the end of October. He ate street food and watched the human-powered ferris wheels</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1728-01579B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            96.173526,16.840939,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Morning Star Tea House</name>
        <description>Not sure if this location still exists, the CNN site says it is on Saya San Road, but not showing up on the map. Tony met with San Zarni Bo and had fermented tea leaf salad, which is served with peanuts, lime, and chilies.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            96.1588334,16.818613,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Old Bagan</name>
        <description>Tony and Philippe traveled on a train through the Burmese country to Bagan. They bought snacks from locals at the train station. The train ride was very bumpy.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1716-AFB42B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            94.8585458,21.1717271,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Sarabha Restaurant</name>
        <description>Tony ate at a small food stand near the Bagan Palace ruins and called it the best restaurant in the country so far. He had chicken curry and raved about all the small accompaniments served.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            94.8652428,21.1725968,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Bagan Palace Ruins</name>
        <description>Tony and Philippe visited the palace ruins and admired the structures</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1523-01579B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            94.8620167,21.1714096,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>19th Street Night Market</name>
        <description>Tony met with a local punk band at this night market.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-1A237E</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            96.1495051,16.7772208,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Kaung Myat Restaurant</name>
        <description>Tony and the punk band ate barbecue at this stand in the night market.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            96.1495797,16.7755816,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Koreatown Plaza</name>
        <description>Tony and Roy Choi viewed Koreatown from the roof of this building, and talked about the 1992 Rodney King riots that took place below.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1523-01579B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -118.3088155,34.0551296,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Dong Il Jang Restaurant</name>
        <description>Tony ate with Roy Choi and Roy Kim, the grandson of the founder of the restaurant. They had banchan, bulgogi, sliced ribeye, kimchi bokumbap (fried rice)</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -118.3049389,34.0579389,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Kogi Taco Truck</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Roy Choi's Korean taco truck. Tony had the Kogi short rib taco, a Korean barbecue short rib on corn tortilla with salsa roja, cilantro, and onion, slaw, and a chili soy vinaigrette.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1722-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -118.2514154,34.0523868,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Chego</name>
        <description><![CDATA[At the time of filming, this was a food truck, but has since been made into a brick & mortar establishment. Roy Choi took Tony there and he ate a Kimchi Spam Bowl.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1722-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -118.2396111,34.0613819,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>A-Frame (Closed)</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Former site of Roy Choi's A-Frame restaurant.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-BDBDBD</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -118.4322729,33.9970482,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Sizzler</name>
        <description><![CDATA[After meeting at David Choe's secret studio where David painted Tony's portrait, the two went to Sizzler to eat. David introduced Tony to his creation, the Salad bar meatball taco.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -118.2914272,34.0668481,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Swadesh Restaurant and Grocery Store</name>
        <description>Tony had curried goat, samosas, tandoori chicken, fish curry with chilis in this area called Little Bangladesh</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -118.3046422,34.0691926,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Jollibee</name>
        <description>Tony and Roy had an Aloha burger, Spam Little Big Bite sandwich, and Halo-Halo, which Tony described as an “oddly beautiful” dessert with  sweet red beans, white beans, red and green jello, young white coconut, flan, ice cream, and shaved ice.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1530-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -118.2929497,34.0765403,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name><![CDATA[David Choe's parents' house]]></name>
        <description><![CDATA[David Choe bought his parents a house in Los Feliz. Tony and David visited the home and Jane Choe, David's mom, cooked for them. She made beef ribs stew, kimchi, chestnut rice, stuffed peppers, seaweed and jellied mung bean, japchae with shiitake, avocado eggrolls, fried squid, potato pancake.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1603-9C27B0</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -118.2848199,34.1063307,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Myung In Dumplings</name>
        <description>Tony and David Choe had Wang mandu king dumplings (with pork and kimchi inside), mandu dumplings (smaller with thinner dumping skins), and sweet dumplings.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -118.3035009,34.0528785,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Monte Carlo Bar</name>
        <description>Tony and David Choe went to this dive bar that Tony loved.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1517-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -118.2922396,34.0688678,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Beverly Soon Tofu Restaurant</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony and Roy Choi visited this place that Roy said was one of his favorites. They serve a soup called Soon Dubu, described by Tony as "a fiery, tongue-searing, ass-burning tofu soup that will make you forget every bad thing you ever thought about tofu."]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1640-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -118.2925329,34.0530587,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>La Vanguardia Airport</name>
        <description><![CDATA["On first inspection, this is an airplane boneyard, where unwanted props from Romancing the Stone corrode artfully. But in reality, this sleepy hangar is an important gateway to the more impenetrable parts of the country," Tony says.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1504-0288D1</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -73.6121682,4.168983,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Miraflores</name>
        <description>The plane landed here in Miraflores, a jungle outpost in the southern province of Guaviare in the Amazon Forest Preserve. Tony talked with a guide there about the cocaine trade of the past.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1504-0288D1</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -71.9519884,1.3385176,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Paloquemao</name>
        <description>A large market, where Tony met with a guide to have some fresh carrot and orange juice. They also ate corn arepas. In the back corner of the fish market, they had Caldo de Costilla, a traditional breakfast soup from the Andean region, which has beef short ribs in a broth with potatoes and scallions.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-673AB7</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -74.0838729,4.6148025,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>La Puerta Falsa</name>
        <description>Tony met with Hector Abad, a writer. They ate tamales with chicken and pork belly.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -74.0748138,4.5980134,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Tábula</name>
        <description>Tony met with chef and musician Tomas Rueda, and they had crab salad, handmade pasta, stuffed with labneh cheese with a chorizo sauce; braised osso buco (with beef shank) over vegetables, wine and broth in a wood-fired oven.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -74.0674637,4.6157859,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Social Club Los Amigos</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony met with a band called On the Tropica to play tejo, a game involving "alcohol and explosives." They also ate a Colombian picada, "a huge selection of fried pork, pork rib, steak, cassava, potatoes, and deep fried plantain."]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1794-FF5252</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -76.5010834,3.4518249,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Sevicheria Guapi</name>
        <description>The Cali version of ceviche: cooked shrimp, slathered in mayonnaise, ketchup, and Worcestershire sauce; rock mollusk with rice; steamed shrimp with green tomatoes; beer; sugar cane (viche), plantains.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1573-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -76.5266746,3.4312864,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Goat vendor</name>
        <description>Tony met Chef Juan Pablo Mayorga in this town in La Guajira. They ate Frichi, a traditional dish from the Wayuu people, includes the offal of the goat. They then rode ATVs.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -72.9167838,11.5384151,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Mayapo beaches</name>
        <description>Tony rested on the beach after crashing on his ATV, had beer, and ate at a restaurant called Mar Azul (which I could not find on the map). They had cazuela, which is a fish chowder made with lobster, fish, shrimp, clams, and conch.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-0288D1</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -72.7667903,11.6792186,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Ice Fishing on the St. Lawrence</name>
        <description>Tony visited in the winter time and met up with chefs Fred Morin and David McMillan of Joe Beef. They went ice fishing on the St. Lawrence River, then ate a fancy meal in the small cottage on the ice.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1573-0288D1</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -73.5152081,45.5518457,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name><![CDATA[Chef Martin Picard's home]]></name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony ate beaver at Chef Martin Picard's home.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1603-9C27B0</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -74.0997408,45.5704884,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Vinet Park</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony watched a game of "shinny hockey," a pickup game of street hockey played on the ice. Meanwhile they ate Choucroute garnie a l'alsacienne (lots of meats and sausages piled on a plate).]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1805-E65100</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -73.5760689,45.4838859,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Gare Centrale Train Station</name>
        <description>Tony, along with chefs Fred Morin and David McMillian, traveled by train to Quebec City. The chefs brought along a gourmet meal including foie gras and truffles.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1716-7CB342</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -73.5665224,45.5001121,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Le Continental</name>
        <description>Old style restaurant. Lots of tableside service including caesar salad, beef tartare, and shrimp cocktail. David McMillian had the filet mignon, Fred had the Scampi Newberg, Tony had the Dover Sole</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -71.2069617,46.8118969,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name><![CDATA[L'Affaire est Ketchup]]></name>
        <description><![CDATA[The restaurant name means "Everything's Cool" in local slang. They had razor clams, a cream of haddock roe, Coqui St. Jacques, terrine of foie gras, head cheese with cassis mustard, truffled sweetbreads, goose hearts persillade, salt cod.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -71.2305139,46.8124389,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Bistro M Sur Masson (Closed)</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony met with journalist Patrick Lagacé at this restaurant (closed in 2016). They discussed "pastagate" which is the scandal that happened when a restaurant got in trouble for using the word "pasta" which is Italian]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-BDBDBD</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -73.5748491,45.547812,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name><![CDATA[Wilensky's Light Lunch Inc]]></name>
        <description><![CDATA[Open since 1932, Tony had the "special,” a beef bologna and salami sandwich with mustard heated on a sandwich press, an egg cream.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -73.5947831,45.5233617,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Cabane à Sucre Au Pied De Cochon</name>
        <description>Tony had a meal here that started with a tower of maple desserts. It had a lot of courses which would be too many to list!</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -74.0528002,45.5722339,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Liverpool House</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Sister restaurant to Joe Beef. Tony met with the chefs and ate Pakistani food by Chef Omar. "Butter chicken crab; little eggplants braised with anar seeds, pomegranate; mushrooms; rabbit korma; fingerlings with fenugreek and fennel; donkey nahari; goat biryani; and more.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -73.575425,45.4829994,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Canadiens de Montréal</name>
        <description>Tony went with the chefs to watch the Montreal Canadiens play the Carolina Hurricanes at the stadium</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1805-E65100</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -73.5694044,45.4961558,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Café Tinjis</name>
        <description>Tony had espresso with Jonathan Dawson, British journalist</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1534-795548</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -5.810855,35.7855561,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Saveur de Poisson</name>
        <description>Restaurant serving tagine. Tony had fresh olives; roasted walnuts; warm bread; tagine with baby shark, calamari, and monkfish with fresh mountain spinach; shark kebabs; strawberries, pine nuts, and honey</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -5.8124525,35.7825508,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Café Baba</name>
        <description><![CDATA[A cafe serving hashish. "There is one particular cafe in the heart of the kasbah that's drawn in foreign dignitaries, rock stars, aristocrats, and artists since it opened its doors in 1943," Tony explained. Afterward they went directly across the street to a vendor selling spanish omelets filled with potatoes, eggs, ketchup, and mayonnaise.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1705-795548</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -5.8115352,35.7879908,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Grand Socco</name>
        <description>Tony met with photographer Cherie Nutting and went to this outdoor food market. Tony bought fresh goat cheese wrapped in palm leaves and some flatbread for breakfast.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1578-673AB7</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -5.8131351,35.7843316,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Boutique Majid</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Antique shop Tony visited and bought a mortar & pestle style tool from the Gond tribe in Mali for $300.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1684-006064</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -5.8107906,35.7867074,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Restaurant Andalus</name>
        <description>Tony ate lunch at this locals only place, with Majid, the owner of Boutique Majid. Tomatoes brushed with local olive oil, garlic, and coriander; beef liver kebabs grilled over charcoal; swordfish; orange roughy. </description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -5.8104184,35.7857228,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Tangier</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony visited Christopher Gibbs' house (antiques dealer and expat) for a garden dinner party with other expats.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1603-9C27B0</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -5.8339543,35.7594651,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Bocadillo Abdelmalik</name>
        <description>Tony had a tuna bocadillo here: Spanish style sandwiches with tuna, veggies, and hard-cooked eggs, a healthy wad of mayo, and a crispy layer of french fries in the sandwich.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -5.8122883,35.7803135,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name><![CDATA[Martyrs' Square]]></name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony watched as kids skating, fireworks being set off, motorcycles drove around as people celebrated the Prophet Mohammed's birthday and freedom after 50 years of oppression.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1523-0288D1</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            13.1811724,32.8949314,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>مطعم بركودا 1‎</name>
        <description>Barakoda Restaurant, a seafood restaurant just outside of town on the Mediterranean. The menu is not printed, you select fish from the daily catch on ice and they cook it for you the way you specify. Tony ate fish, shrimp, and stuffed calamari</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            13.2263522,32.9051756,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Tripoli</name>
        <description>Tony went to a men-only coffeehouse called Yahzakem Coffee where people smoked hookah and drank local coffee.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1534-795548</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            13.1913383,32.8872094,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Tripoli Libia</name>
        <description>Somewhere in Tripoli, Tony ate at a place called Uncle Kentucky (or Kentaki) Fried Chicken. Could not find it on any maps.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-BDBDBD</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            13.1784764,32.8866247,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Bab al-Azizia</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Former site of Gadhafi's palace, destroyed by rebels in 2011. They were told to leave while they were filming this scene.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1523-BDBDBD</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            13.1725929,32.8712117,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Fashloum</name>
        <description>Somewhere in this neighborhood, Tony had a breakfast of sfinz, a donut with an egg on top.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            13.2043175,32.887206,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Radisson Blu Al Mahary Hotel</name>
        <description>The hotel where Tony and the crew stayed while in Tripoli.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1602-7CB342</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            13.1998214,32.8959432,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Misrata</name>
        <description>Tony and crew headed to this town to film, but it was on full lockdown as they approached. They walked around the ruins of the town which showed the damage done when the rebellion took down Ghadafi. Afterward, they killed a lamb and barbecued it on the coast of the Mediterranean</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1523-0288D1</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            15.0992556,32.3255884,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Leptis Magna</name>
        <description><![CDATA[They stopped to get a liver sandwich at a stand on the way to this spot. Leptis Magna, "arguably the most intact remains of a Roman city in the world."]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1523-0288D1</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            14.2948353,32.6343016,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Pucusana</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Coque Ossio, one of the most successful chefs in Peru, spends weekends in Pucusana, a small fishing village. His mom, Marisa Guiulfo, is like Peru's Julia Child. They made food and pisco sours for Tony and Eric Ripert. Marisa opens the house every weekend for a large group to visit and eat.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-0288D1</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -76.7733823,-12.4826088,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Chez Wong</name>
        <description>Tony and Eric visited this restaurant where the chef uses a wok to cook. They had octopus and flounder ceviche; tiradito of flounder with pecan, lime, ají limo chili peppers, and sesame oil.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1573-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -77.02241,-12.0819318,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>ámaZ Restaurante</name>
        <description>Tony and Eric visited this restaurant run by Chef Pedro Escofino, highlighting Peruvian ingredients. They started with a lime cocktail with culantro; breadfruit with tuna and cashew sauce; scallops with wild almond and freshwater shrimp dashi; Inchcape soup made of ham, peanuts, and corn; patarashca (catfish wrapped in leaves and cooked on hot coals); paiche (a type of fish from the Amazon River) atop a palm fruit purée with a fermented yucca sauce and a chili pepper sauce made with nuts and ants. Eric did not like the ants.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -77.0265628,-12.1286763,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Larco Museum</name>
        <description>Tony and Eric visited this museum of pre-Columbian Peruvian artifacts. While there, they went to the erotic gallery and looked at erotic pottery.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1636-FF5252</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -77.0708414,-12.0725026,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Anticuchos Doña Pochita</name>
        <description>Tony and Eric stopped at this  food stand specializing in beef heart, marinated with garlic, cumin, onion, and vinegar and grilled. </description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -77.0322059,-12.0869931,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Chiclayo</name>
        <description><![CDATA[The staging area for Tony and Eric's visit to the mountains to find cacao for their company making chocolate bars.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1523-0288D1</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -79.8549907,-6.7700798,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Mercado Modelo De Chiclayo</name>
        <description>Eric took Tony shopping in this market to find supplies for a shaman they will visit later in the episode.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1578-673AB7</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -79.8389473,-6.7663017,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Marañón Province</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony and Eric stopped at a roadside stand in the Marañón canyon to have sopa de gallina, a Peruvian hen soup. After they went to the cacao plantation, they had dinner at Don Fortunato's home: juane (rice dumplings with boiled egg, chicken, and achiote) and roasted cuy (guinea pig) in a cacao sauce]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -77.0393795,-8.677185,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Mercado Municipal Huacrachuco</name>
        <description>Unsure if this is the correct location. There was a scene on the show where Tony and Eric visited Mercado Central on Calle San Martin in the Marañón Canyon where they bought food to cook to feed their host, Don Elioberto, and his family. They made chicken and shrimp with peppers and onions, along with mashed potatoes and traditional Aztec hot chocolate. I could not find a Mercado Central on a street with this name on the map.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1578-1A237E</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -77.1486686,-8.6056503,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Fatimata Restaurant</name>
        <description>This restaurant is supposed to be in Goma, Rwanda, called Village Fatimata. It specializes in Congolese cuisine like grilled piri piri chicken and gugali. This is the only restaurant with the same name, cannot find it in Goma.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            25.9200848,-2.9499933,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Meal with locals</name>
        <description>Tony visited the Wagenia tribe which live in this region. He had steamed tigerfish limboke: steamed in a banana leaf. </description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1603-9C27B0</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            25.5014537,0.0618759,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Kisangani</name>
        <description>Tony ate at a BBQ kiosk in the city where he had goat stew.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-9C27B0</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            25.2007728,0.5185303,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Meal with locals</name>
        <description>Tony visited this small village town at the base of the Rif mountains and had dinner family style with Bachir Attar, leader of The Master Musicians of Jajouka and his family. Braywine (handformed dough filled with seasoned beef, baked until golden, then crisped in oil); chicken tagine; a wild mountain spinach dish with garlic, cilantro, hot and black peppers, lemon, and olive oil; dessert of fruit and mint tea.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1603-9C27B0</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -5.7280076,35.0229094,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Kisangani Railway Station</name>
        <description>Tony visited this rail station that the Belgians built during their occupation of the Congo. About 200 volunteers still work at the station to keep it running. Tony took a ride on the train</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1716-AFB42B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            25.1904836,0.4996114,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Congo River</name>
        <description>Tony had a dream to travel on the Congo River. He cooked some coq au vin on the boat. Later he and crew were stuck here due to technical issues with transportation</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1523-0288D1</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            17.7651218,-0.6028373,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Yangambi</name>
        <description>National Institute for Agronomic Study of the Belgian Congo is located here and Tony met with a man who works to save the library of thousands of books here. </description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1523-0288D1</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            24.4529792,0.8070691,0
