      <Placemark>
        <name>Waffle House</name>
        <description>Chef Sean Brock introduced Tony to the wonders of the Waffle House, the only place for late night eats in the area. They had pecan waffles, patty melt cheeseburger, green salad with Thousand Island dressing, thin-cut pork chops, T-bone steak, hash browns</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -79.9662707,32.7807852,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Charleston RiverDogs</name>
        <description>A feeder team for the NY Yankees, Tony met with Bill Murray who is an owner of the team, to watch a game</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1519-FF5252</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -79.9613135,32.790527,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Husk</name>
        <description><![CDATA[One of Chef Sean Brock's restaurants, Tony and Billy Murray had a meal here. "Husk directly addresses Southern culinary traditions using the best of modern techniques, but always, ALWAYS respecting the originals and who made them," Tony says. They had old country ham made from a pig brought over from Spain in the 1500s called asabal, and aged 3 years. They also had oyster pie (a pre-Civil war recipe), shrimp & grits, hoppin john with Carolina gold rice, grilled whiting, suckling pig, creamed corn, and cornbread.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -79.932103,32.778074,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Meal with locals</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Chef VJ Dennis cooked some gullah classics here at Mosquito Beach on James Island, home of Ashley Green. They had local blue crab, garlic shrimp, softshell crabs & conch in a peanut stew with sauteed Carolina squash and zucchini]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1603-9C27B0</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -79.9822838,32.6728088,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>FIG</name>
        <description><![CDATA[Tony ate with Chef Glen Roberts, owner of heirloom grain company Anson Mills. He ate in season soft-shell crab with pasta and shaved bottarga ("which frankly, I'd slit my best friend's throat for"), heirloom rice and peas with suckling pig and chicken confit over Carolina Gold rice]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -79.9315748,32.7823508,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name><![CDATA[Atlantic Game & Tackle]]></name>
        <description>Tony shopped here to prep for a turkey hunt.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1684-0288D1</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -79.8781293,32.8072745,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Meal with locals</name>
        <description>Tony ate with Fig owner and executive chef Mike Lata, Rebellion Farm owner Jeff Allen, and Sean Brock. They had barbecued turkey, pickled pigs’ feet and collard greens, barbecue coleslaw, potato salad with ramps, baked red peas, mac and cheese</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-9C27B0</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -79.9310512,32.7764749,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Scott’s Bar-B-Que</name>
        <description>Out in the middle of the country, Sean Brock brought Tony to this traditional whole hog pit barbecue, a place that has been in business for over 40 years. They do burn barrel barbecue that requires tending to all night long.</description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-1577-C2185B</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>
            -79.4750351,33.743331,0
          </coordinates>
        </Point>
